body:
#### Summary
Hello

I'm trying to create a custom equals for specific fields for the recursive comparison. 

For example, I would like to return true in my custom equals method if actual value is greater than the expected value by 1 (don't ask me why :)):

```java
public class Example {

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Foo actual = new Foo(2);
        Foo expected = new Foo(1);

        BiPredicate<Integer, Integer> greaterThan = (a, e) -> Objects.equals(a, e + 1);

        Assertions.assertThat(actual)
                .usingRecursiveComparison()
                .withEqualsForFields(greaterThan, "bar")
                .isEqualTo(expected);
    }

    private static class Foo {

        private final Integer bar;

        private Foo(Integer bar) {
            this.bar = bar;
        }
    }
}
```

This example works well. 

The problem is that the following example with the same initial values for the both entities also wouldn't throw any exception:

```java
public class Example {

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Foo actual = new Foo(1);
        Foo expected = new Foo(1);

        BiPredicate<Integer, Integer> greaterThan = (a, e) -> Objects.equals(a, e + 1);

        Assertions.assertThat(actual)
                .usingRecursiveComparison()
                .withEqualsForFields(greaterThan, "bar")
                .isEqualTo(expected);
    }

    private static class Foo {

        private final Integer bar;

        private Foo(Integer bar) {
            this.bar = bar;
        }
    }
}
```
I found the reason of this issue:

https://github.com/assertj/assertj-core/blob/43edf5862d5984af1a6882323874091455bdab3a/src/main/java/org/assertj/core/api/recursive/comparison/RecursiveComparisonDifferenceCalculator.java#L206

And I want to know whether is it really necessary to check references here? Is it a bug? My opinion that custom comparators have to be invoked before/instead of this verification.
